<CaseStudy slug="ai-ops-workflow">
  <p class="lead reveal">AI coding agents are capable and unreliable at the same time. They will happily ship broken work, skip the checks, and forget what they were doing between sessions. So I built a layer around one: a set of rules, hooks, and review agents that make its output safe enough to act on, without slowing down the work that is actually low-risk.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The problem: autonomy fights safety</h2>
  <p class="reveal">The usual answers to an unreliable agent are a sandbox or a wall of strict prompts, and both kill the speed that made the agent worth using. The real requirement is narrower and harder: keep the autonomy, but put guardrails on it that actually bite, and only where the stakes justify the friction. A tool that treats a typo fix like a database migration teaches people to route around it.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The approach: layered defense, policy in code</h2>
  <p class="reveal">Rather than one big rule, it is a stack of small ones, each aimed at a specific failure and enforced mechanically instead of by good intentions:</p>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>Tiered process.</strong> A quick triage at the start of every task, is this a reversible one-file change, or does it touch auth, data, or anything public, routes the work to the right amount of process. Small changes move fast; risky ones earn a plan, a review, and a gate.</li>
    <li><strong>A guard hook as the catastrophic floor.</strong> A deny layer catches irreversible operations, secret reads, force-push, destructive deletes, piping the internet into a shell, before they run. It is a coarse net for the unrecoverable, not a sandbox, so everything else still moves at full speed. The policy lives in code, not in a prompt that can be argued with.</li>
    <li><strong>Done means evidence.</strong> A stop-gate refuses to accept "done" on higher-stakes work until real proof appears: test output, a build exit code, a screenshot. Trivial work is exempt, so the gate lands where it matters.</li>
    <li><strong>Adversarial review by separate agents.</strong> On higher-stakes changes, independent reviewer agents are spawned to try to refute the work, with a plain serial pass running alongside to catch what the structured one misses. A finding survives only if it holds up.</li>
    <li><strong>Memory across sessions.</strong> Typed memory keeps goals and decisions intact between conversations, so the work does not drift when the context resets.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">Hardened by a real audit</h2>
  <p class="reveal">The review layer is not theoretical; it was tuned by a miss. In a security audit of one of my own projects, the structured, parallel review pass over-focused its framing and missed an injection bug, while a cheap serial baseline running next to it caught the issue. So the rule changed: always run a serial baseline as a miss-catcher, and add a synthesis step that re-raises systemic patterns instead of dismissing them one by one. The governance improved because it was allowed to be wrong once and learn from it.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">A layer, not a cage, and not the methodology</h2>
  <p class="reveal">Two distinctions matter. First, this is not a sandbox that says no to everything; it is a set of guardrails that bite only on the irreversible and the high-stakes, so autonomy stays intact. Second, it is the enforcement layer, the running machine, not the thinking behind it. The methodology decides how much rigor a task deserves; this system is the hooks, gates, and review agents that make that rigor non-optional inside the actual coding agent.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Why I point to this one</h2>
  <p class="reveal">The hard part of running agents in production is not whether they are capable, it is whether they are reliable, safe, and checkable. This is a working example of all three, in daily use on my own builds including this site: limited autonomy, guardrails that are actually enforced, and a bar for "done" that needs evidence. It is the same posture I would bring to putting agents to work on a team.</p>
</CaseStudy>
